Came here with my wife on a Monday morning when our flight was delayed, so there was no wait. Had it bookmarked for about 5 years when I lived in SF Bay Area, but never went because of the fear of lines. We will go back next time we're in CA, no matter how long we have to wait. Easily the best breakfast we've ever had, and I've eaten a lot of breakfasts. Beignet flight and 2 benedicts (catfish/chicken). Each individual element of all 3 dishes was amazing in it's own way. Every bite on the plate was an amazing bite. A+ service too

Brenda's was recommended by many of my friends. I came on a weekday morning and there was about a 30 minute wait which wasn't bad. I had the fried chicken Benedict, the shrimp and grits, crawfish beignets, gumbo and their famous watermelon sweet tea. Crawfish beignets - the flavor was good but they really skimp out on the filling. I would order again but I really hope they start putting in some more filling inside. Gumbo - skip this. It was horribly slimy from the okra and lacked flavor. I had to put a ton of hot sauce inside this to make it edible. Fried chicken Benedict - it was decent. I mean it's fried chicken so it's hard not to taste decent. If you're in the mood for this, try it. I think I'll order just the fried chicken instead of this dish. Shrimp and grits - I literally would come back to this restaurant for this dish alone. This was THE BEST shrimp and grits I've ever had. Every single part of the dish was perfectly rich and seasoned and I wouldn't change anything about it. This dish really made the whole experience for me. thinking about it is making my mouth water as I write this review. watermelon sweet tea - skip it. I like that there are refills for this drink but I couldn't see why everyone loved it so much. The watermelon flavor is there but for me personally it was nothing extraordinary. The service here was great and the portions were large which makes this restaurant one I would come back to again. I do think this place is overhyped but the shrimp and grits are out of this world and will keep bringing me back here.

Is it worth the loooong line? Maybe. The beignets are done very well, pillowy, doughy and come pippin' hot. The grits are well cooked a tad on the salty side. Is it extremely heavy and rich? Yes. If you feel like eating delicious comfort fried food in a crowded and slightly rushed setting after standing in line for an hour...this is your spot.

The wait here is real, but all in all not horrible. It was cold and raining on a Sunday afternoon, but there was a lovely security guard that made sure we put our name on the waitlist board correctly. Then she told us to head into their sister cafe Libby Jane a few stores down to get shelter from the rain. It was such a sweet gesture, and it totally worked in our favor. (Inside Libby Jane, they serve the same Brenda's chicken sausage gumbo at a cheaper price, so we ended up getting that to hold our hunger at bay). YUM. I want it right now as I type this. After our 45 minute wait, we were seated, ordered our food, and ate it in all its deliciousness. We basically all got either the fried chicken or fried catfish benedicts which were amazing and decently priced. We also got the beignet sampler which were great but I too doughy and heavy for me by the time I finished my benedict, but they were still one of the most delicious things I've ever eaten. I really liked the crawfish and granny smith apple flavors. Just listen to the 10K reviews this place has gotten and eat here if you can.

This place is definitely for foodies. The ambiance is great. Food was served in a timely manner even though it was packed. I give it 5 star because my dish was off the charts. Yes I recommend this place to foodies out there! This kind of food makes one appreciate the art of culinary.

I cannot begin to express how bad Brenda's soul food is. The andouille sausage is a regular brand like Aidell, the French toast is billed as Classic French Toast  ($10.75) "Three thick slices of cinnamon-battered brioche" - except it's regular sliced white bread, not thick, not brioche, no cinnamon, and barely any egg batter. It did however cost $10.75 so they got that bit right. The cream biscuit was passable. I won't be back.

Things to get: beignets. I was a fan of the flight, a plate of four beignets that give you a taste of what Brenda's is all about. The Crawfish is dusted with seasoning, filled with cheese and ample amount of seafood. The dough itself is light and fluffy and I enjoyed it savory. The apple cinnamon literally tasted like an apple donut. It was sweet and gooey. We had added some of the peach jam that was on the table and it was delicious. We saved the Ghirardelli and plain one for home and it wasn't as good as the day of. We did warm it up in the oven and the chocolate did have a ton of chocolate, but not sure if it was anything as special as it being fresh from the oven (obvi). It does get fairly busy, it's cool that you write your name on the chalkboard and it has that New Orleans feel. Not sure how long I'd actually want to wait though. We had also got the Fried Chicken Benedict (~$14) and not sure if I loved it. It was good, but nothing notable. I guess I was expecting more for the hype. The Po' Boy sounded good and their shrimp and grits. Maybe next time? Maybe not. Area's not the greatest so maybe just be aware and go for brunch but dinner's different.

Came here for dinner. I think this restaurant caters to tourists mostly. Portions here are rather small for Southern cuisine. After eating Southern comfort food you normally feel stuffed walking out the restaurant. Not the case here, I was actually still a little hungry. Oh, boy, I had been looking forward to this meal for months, literally. I walked in and was immediately escorted to my seat. The curse of the bay leaf lives on... I had a small family get-together for my birthday at Brenda's. Even though the place was packed, we were seated within ten minutes. The menu looked amazing, especially the beignets. However, they were over four dollars apiece, so we decided on hushpuppies instead, which came four to an order. They were decently sized, and tasted great. I ordered the Red Beans & Rice - Oh So Nice!, which was in fact, oh so nice. The red beans and the rice tasted great, but my favorite thing about the dish was the big, split andouille sausage that lay in the middle. The only downside to the meal was the addition of two bay leaves that I pulled from the stew; thus, the Curse of the Bay Leaf continues. I was also able to sample the shrimp and grits. Even though my dish tasted good, it was nothing compared to the shrimp and grits. Huge pieces of shrimp swimming in a pool of the cheesiest, tastiest grits I have ever had. I had the Creole Bloody Mary, which is as good as it sounds. The pickled okra was a great touch, and the creole salted rim was awesome. Other than that it was one of the best Bloody Mary's I've had. The service was very nice and friendly, and even though the place was crowded, it didn't feel over-crowded. I'm already looking forward to my next trip.

Ordered the BBQ beef briquet and it was amazing. My friends and I enjoyed a fantastic dinner. We will be back

    Brenda's was recommended by many of my friends. I came on a weekday morning and there was about a 30 minute wait which wasn't bad. I had the fried chicken Benedict, the shrimp and grits, crawfish beignets, gumbo and their famous watermelon sweet tea.

    Crawfish beignets - the flavor was good but they really skimp out on the filling. I would order again but I really hope they start putting in some more filling inside.

    Gumbo - skip this. It was horribly slimy from the okra and lacked flavor. I had to put a ton of hot sauce inside this to make it edible.

    Fried chicken Benedict - it was decent. I mean it's fried chicken so it's hard not to taste decent. If you're in the mood for this, try it. I think I'll order just the fried chicken instead of this dish.

    Shrimp and grits - I literally would come back to this restaurant for this dish alone. This was THE BEST shrimp and grits I've ever had. Every single part of the dish was perfectly rich and seasoned and I wouldn't change anything about it. This dish really made the whole experience for me. thinking about it is making my mouth water as I write this review.

    watermelon sweet tea - skip it. I like that there are refills for this drink but I couldn't see why everyone loved it so much. The watermelon flavor is there but for me personally it was nothing extraordinary.

    The service here was great and the portions were large which makes this restaurant one I would come back to again. I do think this place is overhyped but the shrimp and grits are out of this world and will keep bringing me back here.

    1 check-in

    Things to get: beignets. I was a fan of the flight, a plate of four beignets that give you a taste of what Brenda's is all about. The Crawfish is dusted with seasoning, filled with cheese and ample amount of seafood. The dough itself is light and fluffy and I enjoyed it savory. The apple cinnamon literally tasted like an apple donut. It was sweet and gooey. We had added some of the peach jam that was on the table and it was delicious. We saved the Ghirardelli and plain one for home and it wasn't as good as the day of. We did warm it up in the oven and the chocolate did have a ton of chocolate, but not sure if it was anything as special as it being fresh from the oven (obvi).

    It does get fairly busy, it's cool that you write your name on the chalkboard and it has that New Orleans feel. Not sure how long I'd actually want to wait though. We had also got the Fried Chicken Benedict (~$14) and not sure if I loved it. It was good, but nothing notable. I guess I was expecting more for the hype. The Po' Boy sounded good and their shrimp and grits. Maybe next time? Maybe not. Area's not the greatest so maybe just be aware and go for brunch but dinner's different.

    The curse of the bay leaf lives on...

    I had a small family get-together for my birthday at Brenda's. Even though the place was packed, we were seated within ten minutes.

    The menu looked amazing, especially the beignets. However, they were over four dollars apiece, so we decided on hushpuppies instead, which came four to an order. They were decently sized, and tasted great. I ordered the Red Beans & Rice - Oh So Nice!, which was in fact, oh so nice. The red beans and the rice tasted great, but my favorite thing about the dish was the big, split andouille sausage that lay in the middle. The only downside to the meal was the addition of two bay leaves that I pulled from the stew; thus, the Curse of the Bay Leaf continues.

    I was also able to sample the shrimp and grits. Even though my dish tasted good, it was nothing compared to the shrimp and grits. Huge pieces of shrimp swimming in a pool of the cheesiest, tastiest grits I have ever had.

    I had the Creole Bloody Mary, which is as good as it sounds. The pickled okra was a great touch, and the creole salted rim was awesome. Other than that it was one of the best Bloody Mary's I've had.

    The service was very nice and friendly, and even though the place was crowded, it didn't feel over-crowded.

    I'm already looking forward to my next trip.
